# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: wren-language
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:wren-language/bytecode] The name *bytecode* stems from instruction sets that have one-byte opcodes followed by optional parameters.
[src:wren-language/bytecode] Intermediate representations such as bytecode may be output by programming language implementations to ease interpretation, or it may be used to reduce hardware and operating system dependence by allowing the same code to run cross-platform, on different devices.
[src:wren-language/bytecode] Bytecode may often be either directly executed on a virtual machine (a p-code machine, i.e., interpreter), or it may be further compiled into machine code for better performance.
[src:wren-language/bytecode] Since bytecode instructions are processed by software, they may be arbitrarily complex, but are nonetheless often akin to traditional hardware instructions: virtual stack machines are the most common, but virtual register machines have been built also.
[src:wren-language/bytecode] Different parts may often be stored in separate files, similar to object modules, but dynamically loaded during execution.
[src:wren-language/bytecode] A bytecode program may be executed by parsing and *directly* executing the instructions, one at a time.
[src:wren-language/bytecode] This kind of *bytecode interpreter* is very portable.
[src:wren-language/bytecode] Some systems, called dynamic translators, or *just-in-time* (JIT) compilers, translate bytecode into machine code as necessary at runtime.
[src:wren-language/bytecode] This makes the virtual machine hardware-specific but does not lose the portability of the bytecode.
[src:wren-language/bytecode] For example, Java and Smalltalk code is typically stored in bytecode format, which is typically then JIT compiled to translate the bytecode to machine code before execution.
[src:wren-language/bytecode] This introduces a delay before a program is run, when the bytecode is compiled to native machine code, but improves execution speed considerably compared to interpreting source code directly, normally by around an order of magnitude (10x).
[src:wren-language/bytecode] Because of its performance advantage, today many language implementations execute a program in two phases, first compiling the source code into bytecode, and then passing the bytecode to the virtual machine.
[src:wren-language/bytecode] There are bytecode based virtual machines of this sort for Java, Raku, Python, PHP, Tcl, mawk and Forth (however, Forth is seldom compiled via bytecodes in this way, and its virtual machine is more generic instead).
[src:wren-language/bytecode] The implementation of Perl and Ruby 1.8 instead work by walking an abstract syntax tree representation derived from the source code.
[src:wren-language/bytecode] More recently, the authors of V8 and Dart have challenged the notion that intermediate bytecode is needed for fast and efficient VM implementation.
[src:wren-language/bytecode] Both of these language implementations currently do direct JIT compiling from source code to machine code with no bytecode intermediary.
[src:wren-language/bytecode] Compiled code can be analysed and investigated using a built-in tool for debugging the low-level bytecode.
[src:wren-language/class-computer-programming] In programming, a **class** is a syntactic entity structure used to create objects.
[src:wren-language/class-computer-programming] The capabilities of a class differ between programming languages, but generally the shared aspects consist of state (variables) and behavior (methods) that are each either associated with a particular object or with all objects of that class.
[src:wren-language/class-computer-programming] Object state can differ between each instance of the class whereas the class state is shared by all of them.
[src:wren-language/class-computer-programming] The object methods include access to the object state (via an implicit or explicit parameter that references the object) whereas class methods do not.
[src:wren-language/class-computer-programming] If the language supports inheritance, a class can be defined based on another class with all of its state and behavior plus additional state and behavior that further specializes the class.
[src:wren-language/class-computer-programming] The specialized class is a *sub-class*, and the class it is based on is its *superclass*.
[src:wren-language/class-computer-programming] In purely object-oriented programming languages, such as Java and C#, all classes might be part of an inheritance tree such that the root class is `Object`, meaning all objects instances are of `Object` or implicitly extend `Object`, which is called a top type.
[src:wren-language/class-computer-programming] The concept was introduced mostly in object-oriented programming by the Simula language in the 1960's and has been in continuous use in many programming languages since.
[src:wren-language/class-computer-programming] Its creation was based in similar concept as block used in prior-based ALGOL 68 programming language.
[src:wren-language/class-computer-programming] As an instance of a class, an object is constructed from a class via *instantiation*.
[src:wren-language/class-computer-programming] Memory is allocated and initialized for the object state and a reference to the object is provided to consuming code.
[src:wren-language/class-computer-programming] The object is usable until it is destroyed – its state memory is de-allocated.
[src:wren-language/class-computer-programming] Most languages allow for custom logic at lifecycle events via a constructor and a destructor.
[src:wren-language/class-computer-programming] An object expresses data type as an interface – the type of each member variable and the signature of each member function (method).
[src:wren-language/class-computer-programming] A class defines an implementation of an interface, and instantiating the class results in an object that exposes the implementation via the interface.
[src:wren-language/class-computer-programming] In the terms of type theory, a class is an implementation‍—‌a *concrete* data structure and collection of subroutines‍—‌while a type is an interface.
[src:wren-language/class-computer-programming] Different (concrete) classes can produce objects of the same (abstract) type (depending on type system).
[src:wren-language/class-computer-programming] For example, the type (interface) Stack might be implemented by SmallStack that is fast for small stacks but scales poorly and ScalableStack that scales well but has high overhead for small stacks.
[src:wren-language/class-computer-programming] A class contains data field syntactically described (or *properties*, *fields*, *data members*, or *attributes*).
[src:wren-language/class-computer-programming] These are usually field types and names that will be associated with state variables at program run time; these state variables either belong to the class or specific instances of the class.
[src:wren-language/class-computer-programming] In most languages, the structure defined by the class determines the layout of the memory used by its instances.
[src:wren-language/class-computer-programming] Other implementations are possible: for example, objects in Python use associative key-value containers.
[src:wren-language/class-computer-programming] Some programming languages such as Eiffel support specification of invariants as part of the definition of the class, and enforce them through the type system.
[src:wren-language/class-computer-programming] Encapsulation of state is necessary for being able to enforce the invariants of the class.
[src:wren-language/class-computer-programming] The behavior (or action) of a class or its instances is defined using methods.
[src:wren-language/class-computer-programming] Methods are subroutines with the ability to operate on objects or classes.
[src:wren-language/class-computer-programming] These operations may alter the state of an object or simply provide ways of accessing it.
[src:wren-language/class-computer-programming] Many kinds of methods exist, but support for them varies across languages.
[src:wren-language/class-computer-programming] Some types of methods are created and called by programmer code, while other special methods—such as constructors, destructors, and conversion operators—are created and called by compiler-generated code.
[src:wren-language/class-computer-programming] A language may also allow the programmer to define and call these special methods.
[src:wren-language/class-computer-programming] Every class *implements* (or *realizes*) an interface by providing structure and behavior.
[src:wren-language/class-computer-programming] Structure consists of data and state, and behavior consists of code that specifies how methods are implemented.
[src:wren-language/class-computer-programming] There is a distinction between the definition of an interface and the implementation of that interface; however, this line is blurred in many programming languages because class declarations both define and implement an interface.
[src:wren-language/class-computer-programming] Some languages, however, provide features that separate interface and implementation.
[src:wren-language/class-computer-programming] For example, an abstract class can define an interface without providing an implementation.
[src:wren-language/class-computer-programming] Languages that support class inheritance also allow classes to inherit interfaces from the classes that they are derived from.
[src:wren-language/class-computer-programming] For example, if "`class Z`" inherits from "`class Y`" and if "`class Y`" implements the interface "`interface X`" then "`class Z`" also implements the functionality(constants and methods declaration) provided by "`interface X`".
[src:wren-language/class-computer-programming] Object-oriented programming methodology dictates that the operations of any interface of a class are to be independent of each other.
[src:wren-language/class-computer-programming] It results in a layered design where clients of an interface use the methods declared in the interface.
[src:wren-language/class-computer-programming] An interface places no requirements for clients to invoke the operations of one interface in any particular order.
[src:wren-language/class-computer-programming] This approach has the benefit that client code can assume that the operations of an interface are available for use whenever the client has access to the object.
[src:wren-language/class-computer-programming] The buttons on the front of your television set are the interface between you and the electrical wiring on the other side of its plastic casing.
[src:wren-language/class-computer-programming] You press the "power" button to toggle the television on and off.
[src:wren-language/class-computer-programming] In this example, your particular television is the instance, each method is represented by a button, and all the buttons together compose the interface (other television sets that are the same model as yours would have the same interface).
[src:wren-language/class-computer-programming] In its most common form, an interface is a specification of a group of related methods without any associated implementation of the methods.
[src:wren-language/class-computer-programming] A television set also has a myriad of *attributes*, such as size and whether it supports color, which together comprise its structure.
[src:wren-language/class-computer-programming] A class represents the full description of a television, including its attributes (structure) and buttons (interface).
[src:wren-language/class-computer-programming] Getting the total number of televisions manufactured could be a *static method* of the television class.
[src:wren-language/class-computer-programming] This method is associated with the class, yet is outside the domain of each instance of the class.
[src:wren-language/class-computer-programming] A static method that finds a particular instance out of the set of all television objects is another example.
[src:wren-language/class-computer-programming] Although many object-oriented languages support the above access specifiers, their semantics may differ.
[src:wren-language/class-computer-programming] Object-oriented design uses the access specifiers in conjunction with careful design of public method implementations to enforce class invariants—constraints on the state of the objects.
[src:wren-language/class-computer-programming] A common usage of access specifiers is to separate the internal data of a class from its interface: the internal structure is made private, while public accessor methods can be used to inspect or alter such private data.
[src:wren-language/class-computer-programming] Access specifiers do not necessarily control *visibility*, in that even private members may be visible to client external code.
[src:wren-language/class-computer-programming] In some languages, an inaccessible but visible member may be referred to at runtime (for example, by a pointer returned from a member function), but an attempt to use it by referring to the name of the member from the client code will be prevented by the type checker.
[src:wren-language/class-computer-programming] The various object-oriented programming languages enforce member accessibility and visibility to various degrees, and depending on the language's type system and compilation policies, enforced at either compile time or runtime.
[src:wren-language/class-computer-programming] For example, the Java language does not allow client code that accesses the private data of a class to compile.
[src:wren-language/class-computer-programming] In the C++ language, private methods are visible, but not accessible in the interface; however, they may be made invisible by explicitly declaring fully abstract classes that represent the interfaces of the class.
[src:wren-language/class-computer-programming] Conceptually, a superclass is a superset of its subclasses.
[src:wren-language/class-computer-programming] For example, `GraphicObject` could be a superclass of `Rectangle` and `Ellipse`, while `Square` would be a subclass of `Rectangle`.
[src:wren-language/class-computer-programming] These are all subset relations in set theory as well, i.e., all squares are rectangles but not all rectangles are squares.
[src:wren-language/class-computer-programming] A common conceptual error is to mistake a *part of* relation with a subclass.
[src:wren-language/class-computer-programming] For example, a car and truck are both kinds of vehicles and it would be appropriate to model them as subclasses of a vehicle class.
[src:wren-language/class-computer-programming] However, it would be an error to model the parts of the car as subclass relations.
[src:wren-language/class-computer-programming] For example, a car is composed of an engine and body, but it would not be appropriate to model an engine or body as a subclass of a car.
[src:wren-language/class-computer-programming] In object-oriented modeling these kinds of relations are typically modeled as object properties.
[src:wren-language/class-computer-programming] In this example, the `Car` class would have a property called `parts`.
[src:wren-language/class-computer-programming] `parts` would be typed to hold a collection of objects, such as instances of `Body`, `Engine`, `Tires`, etc.
[src:wren-language/class-computer-programming] Object modeling languages such as UML include capabilities to model various aspects of "part of" and other kinds of relations – data such as the cardinality of the objects, constraints on input and output values, etc.
[src:wren-language/class-computer-programming] This information can be utilized by developer tools to generate additional code besides the basic data definitions for the objects, such as error checking on get and set methods.
[src:wren-language/class-computer-programming] One important question when modeling and implementing a system of object classes is whether a class can have one or more superclasses.
[src:wren-language/class-computer-programming] In the real world with actual sets, it would be rare to find sets that did not intersect with more than one other set.
[src:wren-language/class-computer-programming] However, while some systems such as Flavors and CLOS provide a capability for more than one parent to do so at run time introduces complexity that many in the object-oriented community consider antithetical to the goals of using object classes in the first place.
[src:wren-language/class-computer-programming] Understanding which class will be responsible for handling a message can get complex when dealing with more than one superclass.
[src:wren-language/class-computer-programming] If used carelessly this feature can introduce some of the same system complexity and ambiguity classes were designed to avoid.
[src:wren-language/class-computer-programming] Most modern object-oriented languages such as Smalltalk and Java require single inheritance at run time.
[src:wren-language/class-computer-programming] For these languages, multiple inheritance may be useful for modeling but not for an implementation.
[src:wren-language/class-computer-programming] However, semantic web application objects do have multiple superclasses.
[src:wren-language/class-computer-programming] The volatility of the Internet requires this level of flexibility and the technology standards such as the Web Ontology Language (OWL) are designed to support it.
[src:wren-language/class-computer-programming] A similar issue is whether or not the class hierarchy can be modified at run time.
[src:wren-language/class-computer-programming] Languages such as Flavors, CLOS, and Smalltalk all support this feature as part of their meta-object protocols.
[src:wren-language/class-computer-programming] Since classes are themselves first-class objects, it is possible to have them dynamically alter their structure by sending them the appropriate messages.
[src:wren-language/class-computer-programming] Other languages that focus more on strong typing such as Java and C++ do not allow the class hierarchy to be modified at run time.
[src:wren-language/class-computer-programming] Semantic web objects have the capability for run time changes to classes.
[src:wren-language/class-computer-programming] The rationale is similar to the justification for allowing multiple superclasses, that the Internet is so dynamic and flexible that dynamic changes to the hierarchy are required to manage this volatility.
[src:wren-language/class-computer-programming] Although many class-based languages support inheritance, inheritance is not an intrinsic aspect of classes.
[src:wren-language/class-computer-programming] Classic Visual Basic) supports classes yet does not support inheritance.
[src:wren-language/class-computer-programming] A programming language may support various class relationship features.
[src:wren-language/class-computer-programming] Classes can be composed of other classes, thereby establishing a compositional relationship between the enclosing class and its embedded classes.
[src:wren-language/class-computer-programming] Compositional relationship between classes is also commonly known as a *has-a* relationship.
[src:wren-language/class-computer-programming] For example, a class `Car` could be composed of and contain a class `Engine`.
[src:wren-language/class-computer-programming] One aspect of composition is containment, which is the enclosure of component instances by the instance that has them.
[src:wren-language/class-computer-programming] If an enclosing object contains component instances by value, the components and their enclosing object have a similar lifetime.
[src:wren-language/class-computer-programming] If the components are contained by reference, they may not have a similar lifetime.
[src:wren-language/class-computer-programming] This Car class *has* an instance of NSString (a string object), Engine, and NSArray (an array object).
[src:wren-language/class-computer-programming] Classes can be *derived* from one or more existing classes, thereby establishing a hierarchical relationship between the derived-from classes (*base classes*, *parent classes* or *superclasses*) and the derived class (*child class* or *subclass*) .
[src:wren-language/class-computer-programming] The relationship of the derived class to the derived-from classes is commonly known as an *is-a* relationship.
[src:wren-language/class-computer-programming] For example, a class 'Button' could be derived from a class 'Control'.
[src:wren-language/class-computer-programming] Structural and behavioral members of the parent classes are *inherited* by the child class.
[src:wren-language/class-computer-programming] Derived classes can define additional structural members (data fields) and behavioral members (methods) in addition to those that they *inherit* and are therefore *specializations* of their superclasses.
[src:wren-language/class-computer-programming] Also, derived classes can override inherited methods if the language allows.
[src:wren-language/class-computer-programming] Not all languages support multiple inheritance.
[src:wren-language/class-computer-programming] For example, Java allows a class to implement multiple interfaces, but only inherit from one class.
[src:wren-language/class-computer-programming] If multiple inheritance is allowed, the hierarchy is a directed acyclic graph (or DAG for short), otherwise it is a tree.
[src:wren-language/class-computer-programming] The hierarchy has classes as nodes and inheritance relationships as links.
[src:wren-language/class-computer-programming] Classes in the same level are more likely to be associated than classes in different levels.
[src:wren-language/class-computer-programming] The levels of this hierarchy are called layers or levels of abstraction.
[src:wren-language/class-computer-programming] In this example, a UITableView *is a* UIScrollView *is a* UIView *is a* UIResponder *is an* NSObject.
[src:wren-language/class-computer-programming] In object-oriented analysis and in Unified Modelling Language (UML), an association between two classes represents a collaboration between the classes or their corresponding instances.
[src:wren-language/class-computer-programming] Associations have direction; for example, a bi-directional association between two classes indicates that both of the classes are aware of their relationship.
[src:wren-language/class-computer-programming] Associations may be labeled according to their name or purpose.
[src:wren-language/class-computer-programming] An association role is given end of an association and describes the role of the corresponding class.
[src:wren-language/class-computer-programming] For example, a "subscriber" role describes the way instances of the class "Person" participate in a "subscribes-to" association with the class "Magazine".
[src:wren-language/class-computer-programming] Also, a "Magazine" has the "subscribed magazine" role in the same association.
[src:wren-language/class-computer-programming] Association role multiplicity describes how many instances correspond to each instance of the other class of the association.
[src:wren-language/class-computer-programming] There are many categories of classes, some of which overlap.
[src:wren-language/class-computer-programming] In a language that supports inheritance, an **abstract class**, or **abstract base class** (**ABC**), is a class that cannot be directly instantiated.
[src:wren-language/class-computer-programming] By contrast, a **concrete class** is a class that *can* be directly instantiated.
[src:wren-language/class-computer-programming] Instantiation of an abstract class can occur only indirectly, via a concrete *sub*class.
[src:wren-language/class-computer-programming] An abstract class is either labeled as such explicitly or it may simply specify *abstract methods* (or *virtual methods*).
[src:wren-language/class-computer-programming] An abstract class may provide implementations of some methods, and may also specify virtual methods via signatures that are to be implemented by direct or indirect descendants of the abstract class.
[src:wren-language/class-computer-programming] Before a class derived from an abstract class can be instantiated, all abstract methods of its parent classes must be implemented by some class in the derivation chain.
[src:wren-language/class-computer-programming] Most object-oriented programming languages allow the programmer to specify which classes are considered abstract and will not allow these to be instantiated.
[src:wren-language/class-computer-programming] For example, in Java, C# and PHP, the reserved word (keyword) `abstract` is used.
[src:wren-language/class-computer-programming] In C++, an abstract class is a class having at least one abstract method given by the appropriate syntax in that language (a pure virtual function in C++ parlance).
[src:wren-language/class-computer-programming] A class consisting of only pure virtual methods is called a *pure abstract base class* (or *pure ABC*) in C++ and is also known as an *interface* by users of the language.
[src:wren-language/class-computer-programming] Other languages, notably Java and C#, support a variant of abstract classes called an interface via a keyword in the language.
[src:wren-language/class-computer-programming] In these languages, multiple inheritance is not allowed, but a class can implement multiple interfaces.
[src:wren-language/class-computer-programming] Such a class can only contain abstract publicly accessible methods.
[src:wren-language/class-computer-programming] In some languages, classes can be declared in scopes other than the global scope.
[src:wren-language/class-computer-programming] There are various types of such classes.
[src:wren-language/class-computer-programming] An *inner class* is a class defined within another class.
[src:wren-language/class-computer-programming] The relationship between an inner class and its containing class can also be treated as another type of class association.
[src:wren-language/class-computer-programming] An inner class is typically neither associated with instances of the enclosing class nor instantiated along with its enclosing class.
[src:wren-language/class-computer-programming] Depending on the language, it may or may not be possible to refer to the class from outside the enclosing class.
[src:wren-language/class-computer-programming] A related concept is *inner types*, also known as *inner data type* or *nested type*, which is a generalization of the concept of inner classes.
[src:wren-language/class-computer-programming] C++ is an example of a language that supports both inner classes and inner types (via *typedef* declarations).
[src:wren-language/class-computer-programming] A *local class* is a class defined within a procedure or function.
[src:wren-language/class-computer-programming] Such structure limits references to the class name to within the scope where the class is declared.
[src:wren-language/class-computer-programming] Depending on the semantic rules of the language, there may be additional restrictions on local classes compared to non-local ones.
[src:wren-language/class-computer-programming] One common restriction is to disallow local class methods to access local variables of the enclosing function.
[src:wren-language/class-computer-programming] For example, in C++, a local class may refer to static variables declared within its enclosing function, but may not access the function's automatic variables.
[src:wren-language/class-computer-programming] A metaclass is a class where instances are classes.
[src:wren-language/class-computer-programming] A metaclass describes a common structure of a collection of classes and can implement a design pattern or describe particular kinds of classes.
[src:wren-language/class-computer-programming] Metaclasses are often used to describe frameworks.
[src:wren-language/class-computer-programming] In some languages, such as Python, Ruby or Smalltalk, a class is also an object; thus each class is an instance of a unique metaclass that is built into the language.
[src:wren-language/class-computer-programming] The Common Lisp Object System (CLOS) provides metaobject protocols (MOPs) to implement those classes and metaclasses.
[src:wren-language/class-computer-programming] It is basically the opposite of an abstract class, which must be subclassed to be used and cannot be instantiated directly.
[src:wren-language/class-computer-programming] A final class is implicitly a concrete class, *can* be instantiated directly.
[src:wren-language/class-computer-programming] A class is declared as final via the keyword `final` in Java, C++ or PHP, or `sealed` in C#.
[src:wren-language/class-computer-programming] However, this concept should not be confused with classes in Java qualified with the keyword `sealed`, that only allow inheritance from selected subclasses.
[src:wren-language/class-computer-programming] In languages like Kotlin, all classes are final by default, while to allow a class to be inherited from, it must instead be marked `open`.
[src:wren-language/class-computer-programming] For example, Java's `String` class is marked as `final`.
[src:wren-language/class-computer-programming] Final classes may allow a compiler to perform optimizations that are not available for classes that can be subclassed.
[src:wren-language/class-computer-programming] A "sealed class" is a class that restricts inheritance to a selected list of classes.
[src:wren-language/class-computer-programming] It should not be confused with the `sealed` keyword in C#, which denotes a final class.
[src:wren-language/class-computer-programming] The list of permitted classes the sealed class may inherit is specified using a `permits` clause.
[src:wren-language/class-computer-programming] `non-sealed` is another keyword used to declare that a class or interface which extends a sealed class can be extended by unknown classes.
[src:wren-language/class-computer-programming] Typically, an executable program cannot be changed by customers.
[src:wren-language/class-computer-programming] Developers can often change some classes, but typically cannot change standard or built-in ones.
[src:wren-language/class-computer-programming] In Python, classes can be created at runtime, and all can be modified afterward.
[src:wren-language/class-computer-programming] Objective-C categories permit the programmer to add methods to an existing class without the need to recompile that class or even have access to its source code.
[src:wren-language/class-computer-programming] Some languages have special support for mixins, though, in any language with multiple inheritance, a mixin is simply a class that does not represent an is-a-type-of relationship.
[src:wren-language/class-computer-programming] Mixins are typically used to add the same methods to multiple classes; for example, a class `UnicodeConversionMixin` might provide a method called `unicodeToAscii()` when included in classes `FileReader` and `WebPageScraper` that do not share a common parent.
[src:wren-language/class-computer-programming] In languages supporting the feature, a *partial class* is a class whose definition may be split into multiple pieces, within a single source-code file or across multiple files.
[src:wren-language/class-computer-programming] The pieces are merged at compile time, making compiler output the same as for a non-partial class.
[src:wren-language/class-computer-programming] The primary motivation for the introduction of partial classes is to facilitate the implementation of code generators, such as visual designers.
[src:wren-language/class-computer-programming] It is otherwise a challenge or compromise to develop code generators that can manage the generated code when it is interleaved within developer-written code.
[src:wren-language/class-computer-programming] In a simple implementation of partial classes, the compiler can perform a phase of precompilation where it "unifies" all the parts of a partial class.
[src:wren-language/class-computer-programming] Partial classes have existed in Smalltalk under the name of *Class Extensions* for considerable time.
[src:wren-language/class-computer-programming] With the arrival of the .NET framework 2, Microsoft introduced partial classes, supported in both C# 2.0 and Visual Basic 2005.
[src:wren-language/class-computer-programming] For example, in C#, a class marked `static` can not be instantiated, can only have static members (fields, methods, other), may not have *instance constructors*, and is `sealed` (is final).
[src:wren-language/class-computer-programming] An *unnamed class* or *anonymous class* is not bound to a name or identifier upon definition.
[src:wren-language/class-computer-programming] This is analogous to named versus unnamed functions.
[src:wren-language/class-computer-programming] Object classes facilitate rapid development because they lessen the semantic gap between the code and the users.
[src:wren-language/class-computer-programming] System analysts can talk to both developers and users using essentially the same vocabulary, talking about accounts, customers, bills, etc.
[src:wren-language/class-computer-programming] Object classes often facilitate rapid development because most object-oriented environments come with powerful debugging and testing tools.
[src:wren-language/class-computer-programming] Instances of classes can be inspected at run time to verify that the system is performing as expected.
[src:wren-language/class-computer-programming] Also, rather than get dumps of core memory, most object-oriented environments have interpreted debugging capabilities so that the developer can analyze exactly where in the program the error occurred and can see which methods were called to which arguments and with what arguments.
[src:wren-language/class-computer-programming] Object classes facilitate ease of maintenance via encapsulation.
[src:wren-language/class-computer-programming] When developers need to change the behavior of an object they can localize the change to just that object and its component parts.
[src:wren-language/class-computer-programming] This reduces the potential for unwanted side effects from maintenance enhancements.
[src:wren-language/class-computer-programming] Software reuse is also a major benefit of using Object classes.
[src:wren-language/class-computer-programming] Classes facilitate re-use via inheritance and interfaces.
[src:wren-language/class-computer-programming] When a new behavior is required it can often be achieved by creating a new class and having that class inherit the default behaviors and data of its superclass and then tailoring some aspect of the behavior or data accordingly.
[src:wren-language/class-computer-programming] Re-use via interfaces (also known as methods) occurs when another object wants to invoke (rather than create a new kind of) some object class.
[src:wren-language/class-computer-programming] This method for re-use removes many of the common errors that can make their way into software when one program re-uses code from another.
[src:wren-language/class-computer-programming] As a data type, a class is usually considered as a compile time construct.
[src:wren-language/class-computer-programming] A language or library may also support prototype or factory metaobjects that represent runtime information about classes, or even represent metadata that provides access to reflective programming (reflection) facilities and ability to manipulate data structure formats at runtime.
[src:wren-language/class-computer-programming] Many languages distinguish this kind of run-time type information about classes from a class on the basis that the information is not needed at runtime.
[src:wren-language/class-computer-programming] Some dynamic languages do not make strict distinctions between runtime and compile time constructs, and therefore may not distinguish between metaobjects and classes.
[src:wren-language/class-computer-programming] For example, if Human is a metaobject representing the class Person, then instances of class Person can be created by using the facilities of the Human metaobject.
[src:wren-language/class-computer-programming] The most popular and developed model of OOP is a class-based model, instead of an object-based model.
[src:wren-language/class-computer-programming] In this model, objects are entities that combine *state* (i.e., data), *behavior* (i.e., procedures, or *methods*) and *identity* (unique existence among all other objects).
[src:wren-language/class-computer-programming] The structure and behavior of an object are defined by a class, which is a syntactic structure, or blueprint, of all objects of a specific type.
[src:wren-language/class-computer-programming] An object must be explicitly created based on a class and an object thus created is considered to be an instance of that class.
[src:wren-language/class-computer-programming] An object is similar to a structure, with the addition of method pointers, member access control, and an implicit data member which locates instances of the class (i.e., objects of the class) in the class hierarchy (essential for runtime inheritance features).
[src:wren-language/class-computer-programming] Encapsulation prevents users from breaking the invariants of the class, which is useful because it allows the implementation of a class of objects to be changed for aspects not exposed in the interface without impact to user code.
[src:wren-language/class-computer-programming] The definitions of encapsulation focus on the grouping and packaging of related information (cohesion) rather than security issues.
[src:wren-language/class-computer-programming] Class-based languages, or, to be more precise, typed languages, where subclassing is the only way of subtyping, have been criticized for mixing up implementations and interfaces—the essential principle in object-oriented programming.
[src:wren-language/class-computer-programming] The critics say one might create a bag class that stores a collection of objects, then extend it to make a new class called a set class where the duplication of objects is eliminated.
[src:wren-language/class-computer-programming] Now, a function that takes an object of the bag class may expect that adding two objects increases the size of a bag by two, yet if one passes an object of a set class, then adding two objects may or may not increase the size of a bag by two.
[src:wren-language/class-computer-programming] The problem arises precisely because subclassing implies subtyping even in the instances where the principle of subtyping, known as the Liskov substitution principle, does not hold.
[src:wren-language/class-computer-programming] Thus, normally one must distinguish subtyping and subclassing.
[src:wren-language/class-computer-programming] Most current object-oriented languages distinguish subtyping and subclassing, however some approaches to design do not.
[src:wren-language/class-computer-programming] Also, another common example is that a person object created from a child class cannot become an object of parent class because a child class and a parent class inherit a person class but class-based languages mostly do not allow to change the kind of class of the object at runtime.
[src:wren-language/class-computer-programming] For class-based languages, this restriction is essential in order to preserve unified view of the class to its users.
[src:wren-language/class-computer-programming] The users should not need to care whether one of the implementations of a method happens to cause changes that break the invariants of the class.
[src:wren-language/class-computer-programming] Such changes can be made by destroying the object and constructing another in its place.
[src:wren-language/class-computer-programming] Polymorphism can be used to preserve the relevant interfaces even when such changes are done, because the objects are viewed as black box abstractions and accessed via object identity.
[src:wren-language/class-computer-programming] However, usually the value of object references referring to the object is changed, which causes effects to client code.
[src:wren-language/class-computer-programming] Although Simula introduced the class abstraction, the canonical example of a class-based language is Smalltalk.
[src:wren-language/class-computer-programming] Others include PHP, C++, Java, C#, and Objective-C.
[src:wren-language/class-computer-programming] In contrast to creating an object from a class, some programming contexts support object creation by copying (cloning) a prototype object.
[src:wren-language/duck-typing] In computer programming, **duck typing** is an application of the duck test—"If it walks like a duck and it quacks like a duck, then it must be a duck"—to determine whether an object can be used for a particular purpose.
[src:wren-language/duck-typing] With nominative typing, an object is of a given type if it is declared as such (or if a type's association with the object is inferred through mechanisms such as object inheritance).
[src:wren-language/duck-typing] With duck typing, an object is of a given type if it has all methods and properties required by that type.
[src:wren-language/duck-typing] Duck typing may be viewed as a usage-based structural equivalence between a given object and the requirements of a type.
[src:wren-language/duck-typing] In some statically typed languages such as Boo and D, class type checking can be specified to occur at runtime rather than at compile time.
[src:wren-language/duck-typing] C# can invoke dynamic typing which behaves similar to duck typing, through the keyword `dynamic`.
[src:wren-language/duck-typing] Duck typing is similar to, but distinct from, structural typing.
[src:wren-language/duck-typing] Structural typing is a static typing system that determines type compatibility and equivalence by a type's structure, whereas duck typing is dynamic and determines type compatibility by only that part of a type's structure that is accessed during runtime.
[src:wren-language/duck-typing] The TypeScript, Elm and Python languages support structural typing to varying degrees.
[src:wren-language/duck-typing] Protocols and interfaces provide a way to explicitly declare that some methods, operators or behaviors must be defined.
[src:wren-language/duck-typing] If a third-party library implements a class that cannot be modified, a client cannot use an instance of it with an interface unknown to that library even if the class satisfies the interface requirements.
[src:wren-language/duck-typing] A common solution to this problem is the adapter pattern.
[src:wren-language/duck-typing] In contrast, with duck typing, the object would be accepted directly without the need for an adapter.
[src:wren-language/duck-typing] Template (also called generic) functions or methods apply the duck test in a static typing context; this brings all of the advantages and disadvantages of static versus dynamic type checking.
[src:wren-language/duck-typing] Duck typing can also be more flexible in that only the methods actually called at runtime must be implemented, while templates require implementations of all methods that cannot be proven unreachable at compile time.
[src:wren-language/duck-typing] In languages such as Java, Scala and Objective-C, reflection may be employed to inspect whether objects implement methods or add necessary methods at runtime.
[src:wren-language/duck-typing] For example, Java's MethodHandle API can be used in this manner.
[src:wren-language/fiber-computer-science] In computer science, a **fiber** is a particularly lightweight thread of execution.
[src:wren-language/fiber-computer-science] Like threads, fibers share address space.
[src:wren-language/fiber-computer-science] However, fibers use cooperative multitasking while threads use preemptive multitasking.
[src:wren-language/fiber-computer-science] Threads often depend on the kernel's thread scheduler to preempt a busy thread and resume another thread; fibers yield themselves to run another fiber while executing.
[src:wren-language/fiber-computer-science] The key difference between fibers and kernel threads is that fibers use cooperative context switching, instead of preemptive time-slicing.
[src:wren-language/fiber-computer-science] Fibers (sometimes called stackful coroutines or user mode cooperatively scheduled threads) and stackless coroutines (compiler synthesized state machines) represent two distinct programming facilities with vast performance and functionality differences.
[src:wren-language/fiber-computer-science] Because fibers multitask cooperatively, thread safety is less of an issue than with preemptively scheduled threads, and synchronization constructs including spinlocks and atomic operations are unnecessary when writing fibered code, as they are implicitly synchronized.
[src:wren-language/fiber-computer-science] However, many libraries yield a fiber implicitly as a method of conducting non-blocking I/O; as such, some caution and documentation reading is advised.
[src:wren-language/fiber-computer-science] A disadvantage is that fibers cannot utilize multiprocessor machines without also using preemptive threads; however, an M:N threading model with no more preemptive threads than CPU cores can be more efficient than either pure fibers or pure preemptive threading.
[src:wren-language/fiber-computer-science] In some server programs, fibers are used to soft block themselves to allow their single-threaded parent programs to continue working.
[src:wren-language/fiber-computer-science] In this design, fibers are used mostly for I/O access which does not need CPU processing.
[src:wren-language/fiber-computer-science] This allows the main program to continue with what it is doing.
[src:wren-language/fiber-computer-science] Fibers yield control to the single-threaded main program, and when the I/O operation is completed fibers continue where they left off.
[src:wren-language/fiber-computer-science] Less support from the operating system is needed for fibers than for threads.
[src:wren-language/fiber-computer-science] They can be implemented in modern Unix systems using the library functions getcontext, setcontext and swapcontext in `<ucontext.h>`, as in GNU Portable Threads, or in assembler as `boost::fibers`.
[src:wren-language/fiber-computer-science] On Microsoft Windows, fibers are created using the `ConvertThreadToFiber` and `CreateFiber` calls; a fiber that is currently suspended may be resumed in any thread.
[src:wren-language/fiber-computer-science] Fiber-local storage, analogous to thread-local storage, may be used to create unique copies of variables.
[src:wren-language/fiber-computer-science] Symbian OS used a similar concept to fibers in its Active Scheduler.
[src:wren-language/fiber-computer-science] An active object contained one fiber to be executed by the Active Scheduler when one of several outstanding asynchronous calls completed.
[src:wren-language/fiber-computer-science] Several Active objects could be waiting to execute (based on priority) and each one had to restrict its own execution time.
[src:wren-language/fiber-computer-science] Fibers can be implemented without operating system support, although some operating systems or libraries provide explicit support for them.
[src:wren-language/object-oriented-programming] Notable languages with OOP support include Ada, ActionScript, C++, Common Lisp, C#, Dart, Eiffel, Fortran 2003, Haxe, Java, JavaScript, Kotlin, Logo, MATLAB, Objective-C, Object Pascal, Perl, PHP, Python, R, Raku, Ruby, Scala, SIMSCRIPT, Simula, Smalltalk, Swift, Vala and Visual Basic (.NET).
[src:wren-language/object-oriented-programming] The idea of "objects" in programming began with the artificial intelligence group at Massachusetts Institute of Technology (MIT) in the late 1950s and early 1960s.
[src:wren-language/object-oriented-programming] Here, "object" referred to LISP atoms with identified properties (attributes).
[src:wren-language/object-oriented-programming] Another early example was Sketchpad created by Ivan Sutherland at MIT in 1960–1961.
[src:wren-language/object-oriented-programming] In the glossary of his technical report, Sutherland defined terms like "object" and "instance" (with the class concept covered by "master" or "definition"), albeit specialized to graphical interaction.
[src:wren-language/object-oriented-programming] Later, in 1968, AED-0, MIT's version of the ALGOL programming language, connected data structures ("plexes") and procedures, prefiguring what were later termed "messages", "methods", and "member functions".
[src:wren-language/object-oriented-programming] Topics such as data abstraction and modular programming were common points of discussion at this time.
[src:wren-language/object-oriented-programming] Meanwhile, in Norway, Simula was developed during the years 1961–1967.
[src:wren-language/object-oriented-programming] Simula introduced essential object-oriented ideas, such as classes, inheritance, and dynamic binding.
[src:wren-language/object-oriented-programming] Simula was used mainly by researchers involved with physical modelling, like the movement of ships and their content through cargo ports.
[src:wren-language/object-oriented-programming] Simula is generally accepted as being the first language with the primary features and framework of an object-oriented language.
[src:wren-language/object-oriented-programming] Influenced by both MIT and Simula, Alan Kay began developing his own ideas in November 1966.
[src:wren-language/object-oriented-programming] He would go on to create Smalltalk, an influential OOP language.
[src:wren-language/object-oriented-programming] By 1967, Kay was already using the term "object-oriented programming" in conversation.
[src:wren-language/object-oriented-programming] Although sometimes called the "father" of OOP, Kay has said his ideas differ from how OOP is commonly understood, and has implied that the computer science establishment did not adopt his notion.
[src:wren-language/object-oriented-programming] A 1976 MIT memo co-authored by Barbara Liskov lists Simula 67, CLU, and Alphard as object-oriented languages, but does not mention Smalltalk.
[src:wren-language/object-oriented-programming] In the 1970s, the first version of the Smalltalk programming language was developed at Xerox PARC by Alan Kay, Dan Ingalls and Adele Goldberg.
[src:wren-language/object-oriented-programming] Smalltalk-72 was notable for use of objects at the language level and its graphical development environment.
[src:wren-language/object-oriented-programming] Smalltalk was a fully dynamic system, allowing users to create and modify classes as they worked.
[src:wren-language/object-oriented-programming] Much of the theory of OOP was developed in the context of Smalltalk, for example multiple inheritance.
[src:wren-language/object-oriented-programming] In the late 1970s and 1980s, OOP rose to prominence.
[src:wren-language/object-oriented-programming] The Flavors object-oriented Lisp was developed starting 1979, introducing multiple inheritance and mixins.
[src:wren-language/object-oriented-programming] In August 1981, Byte Magazine highlighted Smalltalk and OOP, introducing these ideas to a wide audience.
[src:wren-language/object-oriented-programming] LOOPS, the object system for Interlisp-D, was influenced by Smalltalk and Flavors, and a paper about it was published in 1982.
[src:wren-language/object-oriented-programming] In 1986, the first *Conference on Object-Oriented Programming, Systems, Languages, and Applications* (OOPSLA) was attended by 1,000 people.
[src:wren-language/object-oriented-programming] This conference marked the start of efforts to consolidate Lisp object systems, eventually resulting in the Common Lisp Object System.
[src:wren-language/object-oriented-programming] In the 1980s, there were a few attempts to design processor architectures that included hardware support for objects in memory, but these were not successful.
[src:wren-language/object-oriented-programming] Examples include the Intel iAPX 432 and the Linn Smart Rekursiv.
[src:wren-language/object-oriented-programming] In the mid-1980s, new object-oriented languages like Objective-C, C++, and the Eiffel language emerged.
[src:wren-language/object-oriented-programming] Objective-C was developed by Brad Cox, who had used Smalltalk at ITT Inc.
[src:wren-language/object-oriented-programming] Bjarne Stroustrup created C++ based on his experience using Simula for his PhD thesis.
[src:wren-language/object-oriented-programming] Bertrand Meyer produced the first design of the Eiffel language in 1985, which focused on software quality using a design by contract approach.
[src:wren-language/object-oriented-programming] In the 1990s, OOP became the main way of programming, especially as more languages supported it.
[src:wren-language/object-oriented-programming] These included Visual FoxPro 3.0, C++, and Delphi.
[src:wren-language/object-oriented-programming] OOP became even more popular with the rise of graphical user interfaces, which used objects for buttons, menus and other elements.
[src:wren-language/object-oriented-programming] One well-known example is Apple's Cocoa framework, used on macOS and written in Objective-C.
[src:wren-language/object-oriented-programming] OOP toolkits also enhanced the popularity of event-driven programming.
[src:wren-language/object-oriented-programming] At ETH Zürich, Niklaus Wirth and his colleagues created new approaches to OOP.
[src:wren-language/object-oriented-programming] Modula-2 (1978) and Oberon (1987), included a distinctive approach to object orientation, classes, and type checking across module boundaries.
[src:wren-language/object-oriented-programming] Inheritance is not obvious in Wirth's design since his nomenclature looks in the opposite direction: It is called type extension and the viewpoint is from the parent down to the inheritor.
[src:wren-language/object-oriented-programming] Many programming languages that were initially developed before OOP was popular have been augmented with object-oriented features, including Ada, BASIC, Fortran, Pascal, and COBOL.
[src:wren-language/object-oriented-programming] The OOP features provided by languages vary.
[src:wren-language/object-oriented-programming] Below are some common features of OOP languages.
[src:wren-language/object-oriented-programming] Comparing OOP with other styles, like relational programming, is difficult because there isn't a clear, agreed-upon definition of OOP.
[src:wren-language/object-oriented-programming] Some programming languages, like Java, provide information hiding via visibility key words (`private` and `public`).
[src:wren-language/object-oriented-programming] Some languages like Python don't provide a visibility feature, but developers might follow a convention such as starting a private member name with an underscore.
[src:wren-language/object-oriented-programming] Intermediate levels of access also exist, such as Java's `protected` keyword, (which allows access from the same class and its subclasses, but not objects of a different class), and the `internal` keyword in C#, Swift, and Kotlin, which restricts access to files within the same module.
[src:wren-language/object-oriented-programming] Supporters of information hiding and data abstraction say it makes code easier to reuse and intuitively represents real-world situations.
[src:wren-language/object-oriented-programming] However, others argue that OOP does not enhance readability or modularity.
[src:wren-language/object-oriented-programming] Raymond has written that OOP languages tend to encourage thickly layered programs that destroy transparency.
[src:wren-language/object-oriented-programming] Raymond compares this unfavourably to the approach taken with Unix and the C language.
[src:wren-language/object-oriented-programming] SOLID includes the open/closed principle, which says that classes and functions should be "open for extension, but closed for modification".
[src:wren-language/object-oriented-programming] Luca Cardelli has stated that OOP languages have "extremely poor modularity properties with respect to class extension and modification", and tend to be extremely complex.
[src:wren-language/object-oriented-programming] Leo Brodie says that information hiding can lead to duplicate code, which goes against the don't repeat yourself rule of software development.
[src:wren-language/object-oriented-programming] Inheritance can be supported via the class or the prototype, which have differences but use similar terms like object and instance.
[src:wren-language/object-oriented-programming] In class-based programming, the most common type of OOP, an object is an instance of a class.
[src:wren-language/object-oriented-programming] The class defines the data (variables) and methods (logic).
[src:wren-language/object-oriented-programming] An object is created via the constructor.
[src:wren-language/object-oriented-programming] Every instance of the class has the same set of variables and methods.
[src:wren-language/object-oriented-programming] Classes may inherit from other classes, creating a hierarchy of classes: a case of a subclass inheriting from a super-class.
[src:wren-language/object-oriented-programming] For example, an `Employee` class might inherit from a `Person` class which endows the Employee object with the variables from `Person`.
[src:wren-language/object-oriented-programming] The subclass may add variables and methods that do not affect the super-class.
[src:wren-language/object-oriented-programming] Most languages also allow the subclass to override super-class methods.
[src:wren-language/object-oriented-programming] Some languages support multiple inheritance, where a class can inherit from more than one class, and other languages similarly support mixins or traits.
[src:wren-language/object-oriented-programming] For example, a mixin called UnicodeConversionMixin might add a method unicode_to_ascii() to both a FileReader and a WebPageScraper class.
[src:wren-language/object-oriented-programming] An abstract class cannot be directly instantiated as an object.
[src:wren-language/object-oriented-programming] Other classes are utility classes which contain only class variables and methods and are not meant to be instantiated or subclassed.
[src:wren-language/object-oriented-programming] Instead of providing a class concept, in prototype-based programming, an object is linked to another object, called its *prototype* or *parent*.
[src:wren-language/object-oriented-programming] In Self, an object may have multiple or no parents, but in the most popular prototype-based language, JavaScript, an object has exactly one prototype link, up to the base object whose prototype is null.
[src:wren-language/object-oriented-programming] A prototype acts as a model for new objects.
[src:wren-language/object-oriented-programming] For example, if you have an object `fruit`, you can make two objects `apple` and `orange` that share traits of the `fruit` prototype.
[src:wren-language/object-oriented-programming] Prototype-based languages also allow objects to have their own unique properties, so the `apple` object might have an attribute `sugar_content`, while the `orange` or `fruit` objects do not.
[src:wren-language/object-oriented-programming] In all OOP languages, via object composition, an object can contain other objects.
[src:wren-language/object-oriented-programming] For example, an `Employee` object might contain an `Address` object, along with other information like `name` and `position`.
[src:wren-language/object-oriented-programming] Composition is a "has-a" relationships, like "an employee has an address".
[src:wren-language/object-oriented-programming] Some languages, like Go, don't support inheritance.
[src:wren-language/object-oriented-programming] Instead, they encourage "composition over inheritance", where objects are built using smaller parts instead of parent-child relationships.
[src:wren-language/object-oriented-programming] For example, instead of inheriting from class Person, the Employee class could simply contain a Person object.
[src:wren-language/object-oriented-programming] This lets the Employee class control how much of Person it exposes to other parts of the program.
[src:wren-language/object-oriented-programming] Delegation is another language feature that can be used as an alternative to inheritance.
[src:wren-language/object-oriented-programming] Programmers have different opinions on inheritance.
[src:wren-language/object-oriented-programming] Bjarne Stroustrup, author of C++, has stated that it is possible to do OOP without inheritance.
[src:wren-language/object-oriented-programming] Rob Pike has criticized inheritance for creating complex hierarchies instead of simpler solutions.
[src:wren-language/object-oriented-programming] People often think that if one class inherits from another, it means the subclass "is a" more specific version of the original class.
[src:wren-language/object-oriented-programming] This presumes the program semantics are that objects from the subclass can always replace objects from the original class without problems.
[src:wren-language/object-oriented-programming] This concept is known as behavioral subtyping, more specifically the Liskov substitution principle.
[src:wren-language/object-oriented-programming] However, this is often not true, especially in programming languages that allow mutable objects, objects that change after they are created.
[src:wren-language/object-oriented-programming] In fact, subtype polymorphism as enforced by the type checker in OOP languages cannot guarantee behavioral subtyping in most if not all contexts.
[src:wren-language/object-oriented-programming] For example, the circle-ellipse problem is notoriously difficult to handle using OOP's concept of inheritance.
[src:wren-language/object-oriented-programming] Behavioral subtyping is undecidable in general, so it cannot be easily implemented by a compiler.
[src:wren-language/object-oriented-programming] Because of this, programmers must carefully design class hierarchies to avoid mistakes that the programming language itself cannot catch.
[src:wren-language/object-oriented-programming] A method may be invoked via dynamic dispatch such that the method is selected at runtime instead of compile time.
[src:wren-language/object-oriented-programming] If the method choice depends on more than one type of object (such as other objects passed as parameters), it's called multiple dispatch.
[src:wren-language/object-oriented-programming] In this context, a method call is also known as message passing, meaning the method name and its inputs are like a message sent to the object for it to act on.
[src:wren-language/object-oriented-programming] Dynamic dispatch works together with inheritance: if an object doesn't have the requested method, it looks up to its parent class (delegation), and continues up the chain to find a matching method.
[src:wren-language/object-oriented-programming] Polymorphism in OOP refers to subtyping or subtype polymorphism, where a function can work with a specific interface and thus manipulate entities of different classes in a uniform manner.
[src:wren-language/object-oriented-programming] For example, imagine a program has two shapes: a circle and a square.
[src:wren-language/object-oriented-programming] Both come from a common class called "Shape." Each shape has its own way of drawing itself.
[src:wren-language/object-oriented-programming] With subtype polymorphism, the program doesn't need to know the type of each shape, and can simply call the "Draw" method for each shape.
[src:wren-language/object-oriented-programming] The programming language runtime will ensure the correct version of the "Draw" method runs for each shape.
[src:wren-language/object-oriented-programming] Because the details of each shape are handled inside their own classes, this makes the code simpler and more organized, enabling strong separation of concerns.
[src:wren-language/object-oriented-programming] An object's methods can access the object's data.
[src:wren-language/object-oriented-programming] Many programming languages use a special word, like `this` or `self`, to refer to the current object.
[src:wren-language/object-oriented-programming] In languages that support open recursion, a method in an object can call other methods in the same object, including itself, using this special word.
[src:wren-language/object-oriented-programming] This allows a method in one class to call another method defined later in a subclass, a feature known as late binding.
[src:wren-language/object-oriented-programming] Design patterns are common solutions to problems in software design.
[src:wren-language/object-oriented-programming] Some design patterns are especially useful for OOP, and design patterns are typically introduced in an OOP context.
[src:wren-language/object-oriented-programming] Sometimes, objects represent real-world things and processes in digital form.
[src:wren-language/object-oriented-programming] For example, a graphics program may have objects such as `circle`, `square`, and `menu`.
[src:wren-language/object-oriented-programming] An online shopping system might have objects such as `shopping cart`, `customer`, and `product`.
[src:wren-language/object-oriented-programming] Niklaus Wirth said, "This paradigm [OOP] closely reflects the structure of systems in the real world and is therefore well suited to model complex systems with complex behavior".
[src:wren-language/object-oriented-programming] However, more often, objects represent abstract entities, like an open file or a unit converter.
[src:wren-language/object-oriented-programming] Not everyone agrees that OOP makes it easy to copy the real world exactly or that doing so is even necessary.
[src:wren-language/object-oriented-programming] Bob Martin suggests that because classes are software, their relationships don't match the real-world relationships they represent.
[src:wren-language/object-oriented-programming] Bertrand Meyer argues that a program is not a model of the world but a model of some part of the world; "Reality is a cousin twice removed".
[src:wren-language/object-oriented-programming] Steve Yegge noted that natural languages lack the OOP approach of naming a thing (object) before an action (method), as opposed to functional programming which does the reverse.
[src:wren-language/object-oriented-programming] This can make an OOP solution more complex than one written via procedural programming.
[src:wren-language/object-oriented-programming] The following are notable software design patterns for OOP objects.
[src:wren-language/object-oriented-programming] A common anti-pattern is the God object, an object that knows or does too much.
[src:wren-language/object-oriented-programming] Both OOP and relational database management systems (RDBMSs) are widely used in software today.
[src:wren-language/object-oriented-programming] However, relational databases don't store objects directly, which creates a challenge when using them together.
[src:wren-language/object-oriented-programming] This issue is called object-relational impedance mismatch.
[src:wren-language/object-oriented-programming] To solve this problem, developers use different methods, but none of them are perfect.
[src:wren-language/object-oriented-programming] One of the most common solutions is object-relational mapping (ORM), which helps connect object-oriented programs to relational databases.
[src:wren-language/object-oriented-programming] Examples of ORM tools include Visual FoxPro, Java Data Objects, and Ruby on Rails ActiveRecord.
[src:wren-language/object-oriented-programming] Some databases, called object databases, are designed to work with OOP.
[src:wren-language/object-oriented-programming] However, they have not been as popular or successful as relational databases.
[src:wren-language/object-oriented-programming] Date and Darwen have proposed a theoretical foundation that uses OOP as a kind of customizable type system to support RDBMSs, but it forbids objects containing pointers to other objects.
[src:wren-language/object-oriented-programming] In responsibility-driven design, classes are built around what they need to do and the information they share, in the form of a contract.
[src:wren-language/object-oriented-programming] This is different from data-driven design, where classes are built based on the data they need to store.
[src:wren-language/object-oriented-programming] According to Wirfs-Brock and Wilkerson, the originators of responsibility-driven design, responsibility-driven design is the better approach.
[src:wren-language/object-oriented-programming] Researchers have tried to formally define the semantics of OOP.
[src:wren-language/object-oriented-programming] Inheritance presents difficulties, particularly with the interactions between open recursion and encapsulated state.
[src:wren-language/object-oriented-programming] Researchers have used recursive types and co-algebraic data types to incorporate essential features of OOP.
[src:wren-language/object-oriented-programming] Abadi and Cardelli defined several extensions of System F<: that deal with mutable objects, allowing both subtype polymorphism and parametric polymorphism (generics), and were able to formally model many OOP concepts and constructs.
[src:wren-language/object-oriented-programming] Although far from trivial, static analysis of object-oriented programming languages such as Java is a mature field, with several commercial tools.
[src:wren-language/object-oriented-programming] Many popular programming languages, like C++, Java, and Python, use OOP.
[src:wren-language/object-oriented-programming] In the past, OOP was widely accepted, but recently, some programmers have criticized it and prefer functional programming instead.
[src:wren-language/object-oriented-programming] A study by Potok et al. found no major difference in productivity between OOP and procedural programming.
[src:wren-language/object-oriented-programming] Some believe that OOP places too much focus on using objects rather than on algorithms and data structures.
[src:wren-language/object-oriented-programming] For example, programmer Rob Pike pointed out that OOP can make programmers think more about type hierarchy than composition.
[src:wren-language/object-oriented-programming] He has called OOP "the Roman numerals of computing".
[src:wren-language/object-oriented-programming] Rich Hickey, creator of Clojure, described OOP as overly simplistic, especially when it comes to representing real-world things that change over time.
[src:wren-language/object-oriented-programming] Alexander Stepanov said that OOP tries to fit everything into a single type, which can be limiting.
[src:wren-language/object-oriented-programming] He argued that sometimes we need multisorted algebras: families of interfaces that span multiple types, such as in generic programming.
[src:wren-language/object-oriented-programming] Stepanov also said that calling everything an "object" doesn't add much understanding.
[src:wren-language/object-oriented-programming] OOP was created to make code easier to reuse and maintain.
[src:wren-language/object-oriented-programming] However, it was not designed to clearly show the flow of a program's instructions.
[src:wren-language/object-oriented-programming] As computers began using more parallel processing and multiple threads, it became more important to understand and control how instructions flow.
[src:wren-language/object-oriented-programming] Paul Graham believes big companies like OOP because it helps manage large teams of average programmers.
[src:wren-language/object-oriented-programming] He argues that OOP adds structure, making it harder for one person to make serious mistakes, but at the same time restrains smart programmers.
[src:wren-language/object-oriented-programming] Raymond, a Unix programmer and open-source software advocate, argues that OOP is not the best way to write programs.
[src:wren-language/object-oriented-programming] Richard Feldman says that, while OOP features helped some languages stay organized, their popularity comes from other reasons.
[src:wren-language/object-oriented-programming] Lawrence Krubner argues that OOP doesn't offer special advantages compared to other styles, like functional programming, and can complicate coding.
[src:wren-language/object-oriented-programming] Luca Cardelli says that OOP is slower and takes longer to compile than procedural programming.
[src:wren-language/scripting-language] In computing, a **script** is a relatively short and simple set of instructions that typically automate an otherwise manual process.
[src:wren-language/scripting-language] The act of writing a script is called **scripting**.
[src:wren-language/scripting-language] A **scripting language** or **script language** is a programming language that is used for scripting.
[src:wren-language/scripting-language] Originally, scripting was limited to automating shells in operating systems, and languages were relatively simple.
[src:wren-language/scripting-language] Today, scripting is more pervasive and some scripting languages include modern features that allow them to be used to develop application software also.
[src:wren-language/scripting-language] A scripting language can be a general-purpose programming language or a domain-specific language for a given environment.
[src:wren-language/scripting-language] When embedded in an application, it may be called an *extension language*.
[src:wren-language/scripting-language] A scripting language is sometimes referred to as very high-level programming language if it operates at a high level of abstraction, or as a *control language*, especially for job control languages on mainframe computers.
[src:wren-language/scripting-language] The term *scripting language* is sometimes used in a wider sense, to refer to dynamic high-level programming languages in general.
[src:wren-language/scripting-language] Some are strictly interpreted languages, while others use a form of compilation.
[src:wren-language/scripting-language] In this context, the term *script* refers to a small program in such a language.
[src:wren-language/scripting-language] Typically, a script is contained in a single file, and no larger than a few thousand lines of code.
[src:wren-language/scripting-language] The scope of scripting languages ranges from small to large, and from highly domain-specific language to general-purpose programming languages.
[src:wren-language/scripting-language] A language may start as small and highly domain-specific and later develop into a portable and general-purpose language; conversely, a general-purpose language may later develop special domain-specific dialects.
[src:wren-language/scripting-language] Script is a subjective characterization that generally includes the following attributes.
[src:wren-language/scripting-language] A script is usually not compiled, at least not its usual meaning.
[src:wren-language/scripting-language] Generally, they are interpreted directly from source code, or from bytecode, or run as native after just-in-time compilation.
[src:wren-language/scripting-language] A script is generally relatively short and simple.
[src:wren-language/scripting-language] As there is no limit on size or complexity, script is subjective.
[src:wren-language/scripting-language] A few lines of code without branching is probably considered a script.
[src:wren-language/scripting-language] A codebase of multiple files, that performs sophisticated user or hardware interface or complicated algorithms or multiprogramming is probably not considered a script.
[src:wren-language/scripting-language] A script usually automates a task that would otherwise be performed by a person in a more manual way.
[src:wren-language/scripting-language] A language that is primarily intended for scripting generally has limited capabilities compared to a general-purpose language.
[src:wren-language/scripting-language] A scripting language may lack the functionality to write complex applications.
[src:wren-language/scripting-language] Typically, a script starts executing at the first line of code whereas an application typically starts at a special point in the code called the entry point.
[src:wren-language/scripting-language] For example, Java is not script-like since an application starts at the function named `main` which need not be at the top of the code.
[src:wren-language/scripting-language] The following code starts at `main`, then calls `printHelloWorld` which prints "Hello World".
[src:wren-language/scripting-language] In contrast, the following Python code prints "Hello World" without the `main` function or other syntax such as a class definition required by Java.
[src:wren-language/scripting-language] Scripts are often created or modified by the person executing them, but they are also often distributed, such as when large portions of games are written in a scripting language, notably the Google Chrome T-rex game.
[src:wren-language/scripting-language] Early mainframe computers (in the 1950s) were non-interactive, instead using batch processing.
[src:wren-language/scripting-language] IBM's Job Control Language (JCL) is the archetype of languages used to control batch processing.
[src:wren-language/scripting-language] The first interactive shells were developed in the 1960s to enable remote operation of the first time-sharing systems, and these used shell scripts, which controlled running computer programs within a computer program, the shell.
[src:wren-language/scripting-language] Calvin Mooers in his TRAC language is generally credited with inventing *command substitution*, the ability to embed commands in scripts that, when interpreted, insert a character string into the script.
[src:wren-language/scripting-language] Louis Pouzin wrote an early processor for command scripts called RUNCOM for CTSS around 1964.
[src:wren-language/scripting-language] Stuart Madnick at MIT wrote a scripting language for IBM's CP/CMS in 1966.
[src:wren-language/scripting-language] He originally called this processor COMMAND, later named EXEC.
[src:wren-language/scripting-language] Multics included an offshoot of CTSS RUNCOM, also called RUNCOM.
[src:wren-language/scripting-language] EXEC was eventually replaced by EXEC 2 and Rexx.
[src:wren-language/scripting-language] Languages such as Tcl and Lua were specifically designed as general-purpose scripting languages that could be embedded in any application.
[src:wren-language/scripting-language] Other languages such as Visual Basic for Applications (VBA) provided strong integration with the automation facilities of an underlying system.
[src:wren-language/scripting-language] Embedding of such general-purpose scripting languages instead of developing a new language for each application also had obvious benefits, relieving the application developer of the need to code a language translator from scratch and allowing the user to apply skills learned elsewhere.
[src:wren-language/scripting-language] Some software incorporates several different scripting languages.
[src:wren-language/scripting-language] Modern web browsers typically provide a language for writing extensions to the browser itself, and several standard embedded languages for controlling the browser, including JavaScript (a dialect of ECMAScript) or XUL.
[src:wren-language/scripting-language] Scripting languages can be categorized into several different types, with a considerable degree of overlap among the types.
[src:wren-language/scripting-language] Scripting is often contrasted with system programming, as in Ousterhout's dichotomy or "programming in the large and programming in the small".
[src:wren-language/scripting-language] In this view, scripting is glue code, connecting software components, and a language specialized for this purpose is a *glue language*.
[src:wren-language/scripting-language] Pipelines and shell scripting are archetypal examples of glue languages, and Perl was initially developed to fill this same role.
[src:wren-language/scripting-language] Web development can be considered a use of glue languages, interfacing between a database and web server.
[src:wren-language/scripting-language] But if a substantial amount of logic is written in script, it is better characterized as simply another software component, not "glue".
[src:wren-language/scripting-language] Macro languages exposed to operating system or application components can serve as glue languages.
[src:wren-language/scripting-language] These include Visual Basic for Applications, WordBasic, LotusScript, CorelScript, Hummingbird Basic, QuickScript, Rexx, SaxBasic, and WinWrap Basic.
[src:wren-language/scripting-language] Other tools like AWK can also be considered glue languages, as can any language implemented by a Windows Script Host engine (VBScript, JScript and VBA by default in Windows and third-party engines including implementations of Rexx, Perl, Tcl, Python, XSLT, Ruby, Modern Pascal, Delphi, and C).
[src:wren-language/scripting-language] A majority of applications can access and use operating system components via the object models or its own functions.
[src:wren-language/scripting-language] Depending upon the OS version, WSH and the default script engines (VBScript and JScript) are available.
[src:wren-language/scripting-language] Programmable calculators can be programmed in glue languages in three ways.
[src:wren-language/scripting-language] For example, the Texas Instruments TI-92, by factory default can be programmed with a command script language.
[src:wren-language/scripting-language] Inclusion of the scripting and glue language Lua in the TI-NSpire series of calculators could be seen as a successor to this.
[src:wren-language/scripting-language] The primary on-board high-level programming languages of most graphing calculators (most often Basic variants, sometimes Lisp derivatives, and more uncommonly, C derivatives) in many cases can glue together calculator functions—such as graphs, lists, matrices, etc.
[src:wren-language/scripting-language] Third-party implementations of more comprehensive Basic version that may be closer to variants listed as glue languages in this article are available—and attempts to implement Perl, Rexx, or various operating system shells on the TI and HP graphing calculators are also mentioned.
[src:wren-language/scripting-language] A number of text editors support macros written either using a macro language built into the editor, e.g., The SemWare Editor (TSE), vi improved (VIM), or using an external implementation, e.g., XEDIT, or both, e.g., KEDIT.
[src:wren-language/scripting-language] Sometimes text editors and edit macros are used under the covers to provide other applications, e.g., FILELIST and RDRLIST in CMS .
[src:wren-language/scripting-language] Many of these languages' interpreters double as command-line interpreters such as the Unix shell or the MS-DOS `COMMAND.COM`.
[src:wren-language/scripting-language] Others, such as AppleScript offer the use of English-like commands to build scripts.
[src:wren-language/scripting-language] With the advent of graphical user interfaces, a specialized kind of scripting language emerged for controlling a computer.
[src:wren-language/scripting-language] These languages interact with the same graphic windows, menus, buttons, and so on, that a human user would.
[src:wren-language/scripting-language] They do this by simulating the actions of a user.
[src:wren-language/scripting-language] These languages are typically used to automate user actions.
[src:wren-language/scripting-language] Such languages are also called *macros* when control is through simulated key presses or mouse clicks, and tapping or pressing on a touch-activated screen.
[src:wren-language/scripting-language] These languages could in principle be used to control any GUI application, but in practice their use is limited because they need support from the application and from the operating system.
[src:wren-language/scripting-language] There are a few exceptions to this limit.
[src:wren-language/scripting-language] Some GUI scripting languages are based on recognizing graphical objects from their display screen pixels.
[src:wren-language/scripting-language] These GUI scripting languages do not depend on support from the operating system or application.
[src:wren-language/scripting-language] When the GUI provides the appropriate interfaces, as in the IBM Workplace Shell, a generic scripting language, e.g., Object REXX, can be used to write GUI scripts.
[src:wren-language/scripting-language] Likewise, many computer game systems use a custom scripting language to express the programmed actions of non-player characters and the game environment.
[src:wren-language/scripting-language] Languages of this sort are designed for a single application; while they may superficially resemble a specific general-purpose language (e.g., QuakeC, modeled after C), they have custom features that distinguish them.
[src:wren-language/scripting-language] Emacs Lisp, while a fully formed and capable dialect of Lisp, contains many special features that make it most useful for extending the editing functions of Emacs.
[src:wren-language/scripting-language] An application-specific scripting language can be viewed as a domain-specific programming language specialized to one application.
[src:wren-language/scripting-language] A number of languages have been designed for the purpose of replacing application-specific scripting languages by being embeddable in application programs.
[src:wren-language/scripting-language] The application programmer (working in C or another systems language) includes "hooks" where the scripting language can control the application.
[src:wren-language/scripting-language] These languages may be technically equivalent to an application-specific extension language but when an application embeds a "common" language, the user gets the advantage of being able to transfer skills from application to application.
[src:wren-language/scripting-language] A more generic alternative is simply to provide a library (often a C library) that a general-purpose language can use to control the application, without modifying the language for the specific domain.
[src:wren-language/scripting-language] JavaScript began as, and still is mostly, a language for scripting inside web browsers.
[src:wren-language/scripting-language] However, the standardizing of the language as ECMAScript has made it popular as a general-purpose embeddable language.
[src:wren-language/scripting-language] The Mozilla implementation SpiderMonkey is embedded in several environments such as the Yahoo Widgets Engine,and applications such as the Adobe products Flash (ActionScript) and Acrobat (for scripting PDF files).
[src:wren-language/scripting-language] Tcl was created as an extension language but has come to be used more often as a general-purpose language in roles similar to Python, Perl, and Ruby.
[src:wren-language/scripting-language] In contrast, Rexx was created as a job control language, but is widely used as an extension language and a general-purpose language.
[src:wren-language/scripting-language] Perl is a general-purpose language, but had the Oraperl (1990) dialect, consisting of a Perl 4 binary with Oracle Call Interface compiled in.
[src:wren-language/scripting-language] This has however since been replaced by a library (Perl Module), DBD::Oracle.
[src:wren-language/scripting-language] Other complex and task-oriented applications may incorporate and expose an embedded programming language to allow their users more control and give them more functionality than can be available through a user interface, no matter how sophisticated.
[src:wren-language/scripting-language] For example, Autodesk Maya 3D authoring tools embed the Maya Embedded Language, or Blender which uses Python to fill this role.
[src:wren-language/scripting-language] Some other types of applications that need faster feature addition or tweak-and-run cycles (e.g. game engines) also use an embedded language.
[src:wren-language/scripting-language] During the development, this allows them to prototype features faster and tweak more freely, without the need for the user to have intimate knowledge of the inner workings of the application or to rebuild it after each tweak (which can take a significant amount of time).
[src:wren-language/scripting-language] The scripting languages used for this purpose range from the more common and more famous Lua and Python to lesser-known ones such as AngelScript and Squirrel.
[src:wren-language/virtual-machine] In computing, a **virtual machine** (**VM**) is the virtualization or emulation of a computer system.
[src:wren-language/virtual-machine] Virtual machines are based on computer architectures and provide the functionality of a physical computer.
[src:wren-language/virtual-machine] Their implementations may involve specialized hardware, software, or a combination of the two.
[src:wren-language/virtual-machine] Some virtual machine emulators, such as QEMU and video game console emulators, are designed to also emulate (or "virtually imitate") different system architectures, thus allowing execution of software applications and operating systems written for another CPU or architecture.
[src:wren-language/virtual-machine] OS-level virtualization allows the resources of a computer to be partitioned via the kernel.
[src:wren-language/virtual-machine] The terms are not universally interchangeable.
[src:wren-language/virtual-machine] A 'virtual machine' was originally defined by Popek and Goldberg as "an efficient, isolated duplicate of a real computer machine." Current use includes virtual machines that have no direct correspondence to any real hardware.
[src:wren-language/virtual-machine] The physical, "real-world" hardware running the VM is generally referred to as the 'host', and the virtual machine emulated on that machine is generally referred to as the 'guest'.
[src:wren-language/virtual-machine] A host can emulate several guests, each of which can emulate different operating systems and hardware platforms.
[src:wren-language/virtual-machine] The desire to run multiple operating systems was the initial motive for virtual machines, so as to allow time-sharing among several single-tasking operating systems.
[src:wren-language/virtual-machine] In some respects, a system virtual machine can be considered a generalization of the concept of virtual memory that historically preceded it.
[src:wren-language/virtual-machine] IBM's CP/CMS, the first systems to allow full virtualization, implemented time sharing by providing each user with a single-user operating system, the Conversational Monitor System (CMS).
[src:wren-language/virtual-machine] Unlike virtual memory, a system virtual machine entitled the user to write privileged instructions in their code.
[src:wren-language/virtual-machine] This approach had certain advantages, such as adding input/output devices not allowed by the standard system.
[src:wren-language/virtual-machine] As technology evolves virtual memory for purposes of virtualization, new systems of memory overcommitment may be applied to manage memory sharing among multiple virtual machines on one computer operating system.
[src:wren-language/virtual-machine] It may be possible to share *memory pages* that have identical contents among multiple virtual machines that run on the same physical machine, what may result in mapping them to the same physical page by a technique termed kernel same-page merging (KSM).
[src:wren-language/virtual-machine] This is especially useful for read-only pages, such as those holding code segments, which is the case for multiple virtual machines running the same or similar software, software libraries, web servers, middleware components, etc.
[src:wren-language/virtual-machine] The guest operating systems do not need to be compliant with the host hardware, thus making it possible to run different operating systems on the same computer (e.g., Windows, Linux, or prior versions of an operating system) to support future software.
[src:wren-language/virtual-machine] The use of virtual machines to support separate guest operating systems is popular in regard to embedded systems.
[src:wren-language/virtual-machine] A typical use would be to run a real-time operating system simultaneously with a preferred complex operating system, such as Linux or Windows.
[src:wren-language/virtual-machine] Another use would be for novel and unproven software still in the developmental stage, so it runs inside a sandbox.
[src:wren-language/virtual-machine] Virtual machines have other advantages for operating system development and may include improved debugging access and faster reboots.
[src:wren-language/virtual-machine] Multiple VMs running their own guest operating system are frequently engaged for server consolidation.
[src:wren-language/virtual-machine] A **process virtual machine**, sometimes called an *application virtual machine*, or *Managed Runtime Environment* (MRE), runs as a normal application inside a host OS and supports a single process.
[src:wren-language/virtual-machine] It is created when that process is started and deleted when it is closed.
[src:wren-language/virtual-machine] Its purpose is to provide a platform-independent programming environment that abstracts away details of the underlying hardware or operating system and allows a program to execute in the same way on any platform.
[src:wren-language/virtual-machine] A process VM provides a high-level abstraction – that of a high-level programming language (compared to the low-level ISA abstraction of the system VM).
[src:wren-language/virtual-machine] Process VMs are implemented using an interpreter; performance comparable to compiled programming languages can be achieved by the use of just-in-time compilation.
[src:wren-language/virtual-machine] This type of VM has become popular with the Java programming language, which is implemented using the Java virtual machine.
[src:wren-language/virtual-machine] Other examples include the Parrot virtual machine and the .NET Framework, which runs on a VM called the Common Language Runtime.
[src:wren-language/virtual-machine] All of them can serve as an abstraction layer for any computer language.
[src:wren-language/virtual-machine] A special case of process VMs are systems that abstract over the communication mechanisms of a (potentially heterogeneous) computer cluster.
[src:wren-language/virtual-machine] Such a VM does not consist of a single process, but one process per physical machine in the cluster.
[src:wren-language/virtual-machine] They are designed to ease the task of programming concurrent applications by letting the programmer focus on algorithms rather than the communication mechanisms provided by the interconnect and the OS.
[src:wren-language/virtual-machine] They do not hide the fact that communication takes place, and as such do not attempt to present the cluster as a single machine.
[src:wren-language/virtual-machine] Unlike other process VMs, these systems do not provide a specific programming language, but are embedded in an existing language; typically such a system provides bindings for several languages (e.g., C and Fortran).
[src:wren-language/virtual-machine] Examples are Parallel Virtual Machine (PVM) and Message Passing Interface (MPI).
[src:wren-language/virtual-machine] Both system virtual machines and process virtual machines date to the 1960s and remain areas of active development.
[src:wren-language/virtual-machine] Significant advances occurred in the implementation of Smalltalk-80, particularly the Deutsch/Schiffmann implementation which pushed just-in-time (JIT) compilation forward as an implementation approach that uses process virtual machine.
[src:wren-language/virtual-machine] Later notable Smalltalk VMs were VisualWorks, the Squeak Virtual Machine, and Strongtalk.
[src:wren-language/virtual-machine] A related language that produced a lot of virtual machine innovation was the Self programming language, which pioneered adaptive optimization and generational garbage collection.
[src:wren-language/virtual-machine] These techniques proved commercially successful in 1999 in the HotSpot Java virtual machine.
[src:wren-language/virtual-machine] Other innovations include a register-based virtual machine, to better match the underlying hardware, rather than a stack-based virtual machine, which is a closer match for the programming language; in 1995, this was pioneered by the Dis virtual machine for the Limbo language.
[src:wren-language/virtual-machine] In full virtualization, the virtual machine simulates enough hardware to allow an unmodified "guest" OS (one designed for the same instruction set) to be run in isolation.
[src:wren-language/virtual-machine] This approach was pioneered in 1966 with the IBM CP-40 and CP-67, predecessors of the VM family.
[src:wren-language/virtual-machine] In hardware-assisted virtualization, the hardware provides architectural support that facilitates building a virtual machine monitor and allows guest OSes to be run in isolation.
[src:wren-language/virtual-machine] Hardware-assisted virtualization was first introduced on the IBM System/370 in 1972, for use with VM/370, the first virtual machine operating system offered by IBM as an official product.
[src:wren-language/virtual-machine] In 2005 and 2006, Intel and AMD provided additional hardware to support virtualization.
[src:wren-language/virtual-machine] Sun Microsystems (acquired by Oracle Corporation) added similar features in their UltraSPARC T-Series processors in 2005.
[src:wren-language/virtual-machine] Examples of virtualization platforms adapted to such hardware include KVM, VMware Workstation, VMware Fusion, Hyper-V, Windows Virtual PC, Xen, Parallels Desktop for Mac, Oracle VM Server for SPARC, VirtualBox and Parallels Workstation.
[src:wren-language/virtual-machine] In 2006, first-generation 32- and 64-bit x86 hardware support was found to rarely offer performance advantages over software virtualization.
[src:wren-language/virtual-machine] In OS-level virtualization, a physical server is virtualized at the operating system level, enabling multiple isolated and secure virtualized servers to run on a single physical server.
[src:wren-language/virtual-machine] The "guest" operating system environments share the same running instance of the operating system as the host system.
[src:wren-language/virtual-machine] Thus, the same operating system kernel is also used to implement the "guest" environments, and applications running in a given "guest" environment view it as a stand-alone system.
[src:wren-language/virtual-machine] The pioneer implementation was FreeBSD jails; other examples include Docker, Solaris Containers, OpenVZ, Linux-VServer, LXC, AIX Workload Partitions, Parallels Virtuozzo Containers, and iCore Virtual Accounts.
[src:wren-language/virtual-machine] A *snapshot* is a state of a virtual machine, and generally its storage devices, at an exact point in time.
[src:wren-language/virtual-machine] A snapshot enables the virtual machine's state at the time of the snapshot to be restored later, effectively undoing any changes that occurred afterwards.
[src:wren-language/virtual-machine] This capability is useful as a backup technique, for example, prior to performing a risky operation.
[src:wren-language/virtual-machine] Virtual machines frequently use virtual disks for their storage; in a very simple example, a 10-gigabyte hard disk drive is simulated with a 10-gigabyte flat file.
[src:wren-language/virtual-machine] Any requests by the VM for a location on its physical disk are transparently translated into an operation on the corresponding file.
[src:wren-language/virtual-machine] Once such a translation layer is present, however, it is possible to intercept the operations and send them to different files, depending on various criteria.
[src:wren-language/virtual-machine] Every time a snapshot is taken, a new file is created, and used as an overlay for its predecessors.
[src:wren-language/virtual-machine] New data is written to the topmost overlay; reading existing data, however, needs the overlay hierarchy to be scanned, resulting in accessing the most recent version.
[src:wren-language/virtual-machine] Thus, the entire stack of snapshots is virtually a single coherent disk; in that sense, creating snapshots works similarly to the incremental backup technique.
[src:wren-language/virtual-machine] Other components of a virtual machine can also be included in a snapshot, such as the contents of its random-access memory (RAM), BIOS settings, or its configuration settings.
[src:wren-language/virtual-machine] "Save state" feature in video game console emulators is an example of such snapshots.
[src:wren-language/virtual-machine] Restoring a snapshot consists of discarding or disregarding all overlay layers that are added after that snapshot, and directing all new changes to a new overlay.
[src:wren-language/virtual-machine] The snapshots described above can be moved to another host machine with its own hypervisor; when the VM is temporarily stopped, snapshotted, moved, and then resumed on the new host, this is known as migration.
[src:wren-language/virtual-machine] If the older snapshots are kept in sync regularly, this operation can be quite fast, and allow the VM to provide uninterrupted service while its prior physical host is, for example, taken down for physical maintenance.
[src:wren-language/virtual-machine] Similar to the migration mechanism described above, failover allows the VM to continue operations if the host fails.
[src:wren-language/virtual-machine] Generally it occurs if the migration has stopped working.
[src:wren-language/virtual-machine] However, in this case, the VM continues operation from the *last-known* coherent state, rather than the *current* state, based on whatever materials the backup server was last provided with.
[src:wren-language/virtual-machine] Nested virtualization refers to the ability of running a virtual machine within another, having this general concept extendable to an arbitrary depth.
[src:wren-language/virtual-machine] In other words, nested virtualization refers to running one or more hypervisors inside another hypervisor.
[src:wren-language/virtual-machine] The nature of a nested guest virtual machine does not need to be homogeneous with its host virtual machine; for example, application virtualization can be deployed within a virtual machine created by using hardware virtualization.
[src:wren-language/virtual-machine] Furthermore, moving already existing virtualized environments into a cloud, following the Infrastructure as a Service (IaaS) approach, is much more complicated if the destination IaaS platform does not support nested virtualization.
[src:wren-language/virtual-machine] The way nested virtualization can be implemented on a particular computer architecture depends on supported hardware-assisted virtualization capabilities.
[src:wren-language/virtual-machine] If a particular architecture does not provide hardware support required for nested virtualization, various software techniques are employed to enable it.
[src:wren-language/virtual-machine] Over time, more architectures gain required hardware support; for example, since the Haswell microarchitecture (announced in 2013), Intel started to include VMCS shadowing as a technology that accelerates nested virtualization.
[src:wren-language/virtual-machine] Virtual machines are frequently used to isolate applications from one another for security.
[src:wren-language/virtual-machine] This architectural design (used by Qubes OS, Whonix, KickSecure, and Dangerzone) can prevent the spread of malware from one compromised system (e.g. an email client opening an infected document) to another system (e.g. a password manager).
